result.execSummary:
The defendant Julisha Dashay Dodson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Julisha Dashay Dodson in court with attorney Amanda M. Parent.  Defendant Julisha Dashay Dodson in custody.  John Daniel Flynn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Sentencing proceeds.    Upon inquiry of the Court, State advises they have complied with victim notification. Statements by counsel and defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 2: COURT ORDERS defendant to serve 55 days at the House of Correction and 38 days credit. Sentence to commence no later than 8-15-2017 by 5 pm. 

AS TO COUNT 1:  Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to 16CM1135.
 Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 1 YEAR, concurrent to probation on 16CM1135 with the following conditions:
- Complete Parenting Classes.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No contact with victims.

The court ordered defendant to pay the costs during the period of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. The court found that the defendant is indigent and imposed the DNA sample and the DV evaluation on count 2 but waived the surcharges (DNA & DV) for count 1.

 Defendant advised of appellant rights.

Pretrial Sentence Credit, Notice of Right to Seek Post-Conviction Relief.

Defendant Julisha Dashay Dodson in court with attorney Amanda M. Parent.  Defendant Julisha Dashay Dodson in custody.  John Daniel Flynn appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defendant and defense in agreement.
AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2:   Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Case passed until afternoon for sentencing.
